segments.text: What was it that you did for entertainment and recreation?
Well, most of our recreation and entertainment was self-made out there on the drill ground around where we'd play ball, you know.
And each company would have a team, you know, we'd go out there and we'd play.
And actually, DX Bible got some of his football players off of those.
He'd go out there watching.
And I know old Harry Pinson, he's a past mate of mine.
He was just out there playing from D Company and old D actually watched him and he asked Harry to come down and suit up and he made a good football player down there.
I'd say just company games and things like that.
Now we had to go to Garner Hall on Sunday mornings to the chapel.
They cut that out sometime later but except when we were seniors we could
We didn't have to go when we were seniors, but some of us would because they had real good speakers in those days.
And of course, some of the boys would take, would put under the shirt some kind of magazine and be reading during the speech, stuff like that.
But we had to go.
Had to go to the chapel every Sunday morning.
And they'd have, I remember the Knickerbockers from Dallas,
They were great preachers, and one of the boys was quarterback on one of the excellent football teams here, Arthur Knickerbocker.
Well, those Knickerbockers, every year, one or two of them would come down and give a talk there, and then different ones, but they were excellent speakers, and I enjoyed it very much.
And Dr. Zell also,
We didn't have any churches around here then.
Had a YMCA.
But Dr. Bezell held a class, a Bible class, every Sunday morning for seniors if they wanted to come.
Didn't have to.
And then finally they got some guys like Mr. Cofer, who learned English,
And they would hold a Sunsuit class in these different buildings around like over there in the EE building and places where they have chapel.
And that's about, that's the way, that's about our religious, went on that way until about 1920.
And then some of the churches started bringing preachers down here.
I know Reverend Brown came here in 1920.
He died here a few years ago and he was the first
pastor of the Baptist Church here on the campus.
And then the Methodists and others get started until they finally build quite a group of churches here on campus, I think, enough to satisfy all the needs.
Did you ever have visiting lecturers from off campus come out, come in for afternoon or evening lectures like today
Of course there's something going on several times a week of that nature.
Yeah.
We didn't have much of that.
Most of our speakers were on Sunday morning chapel services and we'd have our classes, our subject matter classes would sometimes bring in outside speakers to give a lecture.
Now, you asked what we did off the hours.
On Sunday was a long day, mostly, and a room they and I, we were both, we roomed together here three years.
And we'd go around to the different barns.
We were taking animal science.
And we had an iceberg named Garrigan charge the horses.
He was from Ireland, too.
That barn out there named Garrigan Stables had horses.
And we'd visit with Mr. Garrigan and then this fellow named Sam's.
He was a Scotchman.
He had charge of cattle.
And we'd visit with all these barns around and went way out to F&B station where they had a lot of feedlots out there then feeding cattle.
And we'd go out there and look over the cattle and stuff like that.
Of course that is natural for us to do that because we were raised that way.
with one horses and cattle and stuff like that, and sheep, but there wasn't much else to do unless you sat on the bench under these trees and have a bull session, you see.
A lot of that going on.
I know we had an old boy named Strange, they called him Tanlake because in our English, in our senior English class up there in public speaking,
This teacher would let you pick any subject you wanted to.
An old train picked a subject called Tandilac, that tonic, Tandilac tonic, you know.
And he gave it in the form of, like these, you see these advertisements.
And about you couldn't sleep, you was nervous, and all that stuff.
And he'd say, I've taken one bottle of Tandilac, anybody can sleep with you, and all that stuff.
He made a good one and so they called him Tanak for the rest of it.
So with not much to do you have to think up things like that.
We were pretty well happy because the world itself was slower in those days than it is now.
Communications and everything else was slower and the world was
bigger.
It's getting to be a small world now.
So we, I guess we were, whatever we did was kind of in line with the period we were in.
Many people make any use of the library for... Well, we didn't have much of a library in those days.
That was one of our omissions down here.
In fact, when I was a fish, the library was in one corner of the academic building.
The library before that burned.

And so we didn't have much of a library and each department tried to have its own in addition to that, you know, of the certain of the journals and things that were necessary to really carry on the scholarship program.
And then the Experimentation Library had a library, the Extension Service had one, but
Yes, on Sunday afternoons that library also tried to take the weekly papers of these small towns.
And the Tuley Herald came in here every, was over here on Sunday.
And so we'd go over there and we'd scan the Tuley Herald, you know, those kids from Tuley, you know.
And the other kids the same way.
But we wanted to get the hometown papers, you know.
But I,
The library started growing by the time we were seniors, it had grown quite a bit.
And of course now I think it's a real first-class library.
Did you play any games of any sort in addition to the athletic games?
I mean checkers, chess, dominoes?
Yeah, you'd see some of that in the room.
But there was no place to do that other than in your own dormitory room?
Well, Wyham City.
Okay.
Did you have any favorite instructors?
Well, you know, I've thought about that a whole lot since I got here, and they talk about what fine faculty they've got now, which they have.
But I thought we had as good a faculty then, or the period we were in, as they've got now.
Now, we had some outstanding people.
You take a dean per year.
He was from Virginia and he could have gone anywhere, I guess.
He was a mathematician and he had somebody that was the author of a book that said over there on trigonometry, I believe.
But, Dean Breyer, he was one of my favorites and he taught me one lesson that's been very helpful to me.
When we were seniors,
we had to take courses in sociology.

And the first day of class, this teacher went over what he was going to have, and another boy on the staff decided that being an animal hunter, we'd really like to substitute another course for that if we could.
So we matched, and I had to go see a dean per year.
And I didn't know at that time that the teacher was the brother-in-law of old Dean.
If I had, I'd have been scared to death to go in there.
But I went in there.
And so Dean, he was just one of those Virginia gentlemen.
And make you feel at home, you know, and sit down there and wonder what he'd do for you.
And I told him about the way Bap and I would like to substitute a course over here in Admiral Hudnery for a course we'd take into sociology.
And so he said, put it in right.
that Dean Puryear would never give you an answer unless you wrote him a letter.
And then he had that on file.
So I went back and had to write a letter.
And when I wrote the letter to him, then he answered it and gave us permission to make that change.
But then, if anything came up about that subject later, he had a file on his letter.
Now that was real good.
It sure hit me one time, because when I was a senior, I came back the next year to take graduate work.
And Christmas, they had lost an instructor out here in Alamo-Hudnery, so they needed somebody to take over some courses in 107.
And they asked me if I'd do that.
Said I could still, I was taking three subjects, one master's.
They said, you can drop one subject and take the other two.
And the two I kept, one of them was genetics and one was veterinary physiology.
And so when that term was over then, just about a month before the term was over, I was offered a job at the Santa Fe Railroad as Assistant General Ag Cuts Agent.
And so I asked some of my instructors about it, and they said, well, I said, yeah, go ahead and take that.
Add that to your experience.
You can come back and get that master's any time.
You take your exam on the physiology and genetics and have that behind you and all you need is just the subject and the thesis.
So I took it and took those exams and all.
So when I came back then, February the 1st, the experimentation offered me a job over here as the charge of swine investigations.
And I left the railroad and came back here February the 1st, 1925.
And then I picked, that's when I left.
I left on February the 1st.
Well, I mean, at the end of that year, I left in June.
So I picked up that, my course right at the beginning of that term, just like I left it, you know.
And so they told me, they said, now you better get, the committee told me, you better stay up on your,
genetics and physiology, you're going to have to take that exam, too, when you take it.
Well, I'd already taken the exam, see?
And before I did, I went up and I wrote Dean Perrier a letter and asked him would I have to take them again if I came back, and he wrote me a letter and told me I wouldn't.
So then, I went up there and told Dean Perrier that this committee said that I had to take these exams on genetics and physiology when I finished my term out.
I said, no, I wrote you a letter two years ago.
And that showed you how important that was.
Yeah, I had some favorite instructors, but I don't believe I had a bad one in the bunch.
I just think we had some real good professors.
Mr. Cofer was one of my favorites.
He was an English professor.
Then became a colleague of yours, I guess, for a long while.
Yeah, he was a dandy.
Well, Mr. Brayton.
Mr. Brayton taught chemistry, freshman chemistry.
At the fire.
Brayton Field was named for him.
And he was dandy.
He was really good.
But I just don't believe I had a story instructor.
Did you have any courses under Dr. Francis?
Yeah.
Now, he was a good one.
Did you ever hear the story about that old boy cheering in the back of one of his classes?
I'm not sure that I have.
Well, have you ever been in that Francis amphitheater where they have classes?
Suits go up that way, you know.
Yeah, I've been in there.
Well, that's where the class was, and this old boy was sitting back up there, and he didn't think Dr. Francis would see him, hear him.
Dr. Francis could hardly hear anyway, but he could hear what he wanted to.
And this old boy, he was very big on the floor, and he didn't think Dr. Francis would see him.
So one day, Dr. Francis came to the class, and he saw an old boy sitting up there, so he went back,
got him a piece of rope and tied it to an old wash tub and dragged it down the hall, and acoustics in that building was terrible then.
You could hear it all over the building.
Dragged it down the hall, dragged it up the steps, up the other wall, sat down by the side of him.
Says, fill her full, Rube.
Oh, that Dr. Francis, he was something.
I don't know how A&M kept those high-powered guys like that because that was back in the mud.
We didn't have any sidewalks, didn't have anything.
And they could have gone anywhere.
Like Breyer and Francis and Dr. Ball over in the botany.
We just had a lot of those high-powered guys, I thought.
And John Burns, who was head of the Ambulance Hub Department, he finished here in 1904.
And he's one of the
Charter of Memories that organized the American Society of Animal Production.
But Mr. Burns was an even outstanding man.
He was a full-blood Scotsman.
That's a good Scotch name, you know.
Yeah, when I was in Lubbock, I talked with his younger brother.
You did?
D. Burns.
Well, I'll declare it.
Yeah, I do D. Well.
He was his, let's see, he was here
He was ahead of me.
Yeah, he's retired from the Guthrie, Pitchfork branch in Guthrie.
We talked a little bit about Dr. Brazell a few minutes ago.
What were the general attitudes of the students towards Dr. Brazell as president?
Well, of course, to speak myself, it couldn't have been any better, but there were a few students long, well, about a year after I graduated, long in there, in the cavalry round over there.
The cavalry had some pretty rough
guy in there at that time.
They thought Dr. DeSalle was stupid on them sometimes.
He'd come over to his office at night and he'd see a light burning up there and a little noise up there.
Instead of letting the military take care of that, he took it on himself, which he shouldn't have done.
But he did and they didn't like that and they got with it.
They'd throw water on him when he'd come back home from
go past that Leggett Hall.
Those upside out there had some banisters or something around there, not there now.
And they'd get out there and they'd throw out water on them when they'd come by there.
He left here in 25, went to the University of Oklahoma, and just made an outstanding success there like he did here.
And they built a building up there.
I think it may be the library.
I forget.
They built some building up there named after him.
But I just thought he was an outstanding president.
He did a lot for A&M.
And he came in 14, left 25.
But some of them, he, Dr. Lavelle,
Some of them boyettes down here didn't like him and gave him a lot of trouble.
One reason why I ask is because I always had the impression from, you know, when I first came here that Dr. Brazell was one of the leading lights as an administrator for A&M for many years.
And since that time, though, a man who had been here as a student in the mid-20s brought in a, I guess you'd call it an underground student newspaper from, I believe, 1924 called The Long Bat.
And there was an editorial in there that seemed to indicate that there was some dissatisfaction.
And I think it was, well, one of the issues that came scrapped up many, many times since then is the matter of censorship or inappropriate

you know, not having the privilege to say what you really think, and they made the comment that if you don't think this is true, this was in an editorial, if you don't think this is true that you can't say what you think, well, get up in the middle of the academic building and say what you think, and then count how long it is until the next train comes through, and that's how long you had to stay here.
Well, of course, they criticized Jesus Christ, you know, and
And you can ask a guy like E. McQuillan.
He was a 20-man.
He was under Brazil.
I'll bet you he would give them a real A-1 rating.
Well, almost everybody I have talked to has done so, and this makes his editorial in his underground newspaper even more puzzling.
Yeah.
Well, I don't know why anyone would do that.
Dr. Bell, he was...
You remember we were, in those periods, discipline was number one.
You had to have, you couldn't get by stuff like you do now, you know.
The old timers believed in discipline and law and order and all that kind of stuff.
And Dr. Zell was in that period and, you know, before Dr. Zell came here,
There'd been guys canned out of here smoking cigarettes on the campus.
You couldn't even smoke a cigarette.
And up at Baylor, Pat Depp and that bunch of guys, well, they'd can you out of Baylor right now if you were smoking up there in those days.
But when Dr. Bell had been here after the war,
all that changed a little bit because during the war you know everybody's and all the company and all had the cigarettes and stuff like that.
I wondered you know after my initial reaction to this editorial and the
comments I had had about Dr. Brazell since then, I wondered whether perhaps that editorial was aimed at the commandant instead of...
It could have been at the commandant, yeah.
It wasn't Ike Ashburn, though.
It was that fellow Muller before him.
He was pretty hard.
Muller was commandant when you were here as a student?
Yes, Fish, yeah.
And was he followed by Ashburn?
Yeah.
during your sophomore year.
Yeah, the aspirin.
The aspirin was real good.
He stayed on for all of the... See, aspirin came back from the war, from the major.
And he's the one who got that cigarette thing changed, I think.
And a few things changed like that.
But he was a lovable fellow, that fellow aspirin was.
He was later, I think...
on Dr. Walton's staff.
Dr. Walton was made president following Brazell.
I believe, I know he, Ashburn served in a number of capacities as an information officer and some things of that nature.
Yeah.
So, but he was very highly regarded then.
Oh yeah, yeah, he was a danger.
He was out of the military though.
Yes, that's right.
He was out of the military.
Dr. Brazell was
Dr. Rozelle was really highly regarded by his staff here.
And I was, when I came back from my masters, a guy named Johnston and Hooten Williams.
Hooten Williams was one of the good, best basketball players here.
Williamson Johnson were chemistry majors, and I was animal science.
We came back here to work on our matches, and they put us over there in Austin Hall, which is not here anymore.
That is one of the old dormitories.
It wasn't much of a dormitory.
They had to carry wood.
So they put us in there, and we didn't want to be there.
We wanted to be in Alpha Hall.
Of course, it's gone now, too.
But it's bigger, and the rooms are bigger, and we thought it would be better for us.
We could study better.
So we went to Dr. Brazell, and these other two boys were at a class, and they asked me to go.
And I went up to see Dr. Brazell, and when I told him the problem, he just got up out of his chair and said, let's go down to the commandant's office.
That's what I came for.
And there was some military men in there at the same time.
We went in, and when Dr. Brazell came in, everybody came to his feet.
They respected Dr. Zell and treated him real royal.
And Dr. Zell got that chance.
He just asked, he didn't, he wasn't adamant about it.
He just says, we have three students, Colonel Ashburn, call him Colonel, or yeah, I believe it, that would like to room over in Alfa Hall and say, you think you could arrange that?
He says, here we go.
Oh yeah, he says, we can do this.
That's all there was to it.
But I was impressed the way they came to their feet when he entered the door.
I believe I've been told that Alpha and Beta were places where non-military students lived.
Yes, they did, and then some graduate students.
Were there graduate students primarily in Austin Hall, too?
Well, I don't know.
We thought it was used at that time for waiters over in MS Hall, some of them.
Speezer was, he was Spanish or some kind of a thing.
I knew Speezer.
But I think he got some of his boys out of Puerto Rico and I don't know where else.
But I think they, it was over there.
But Alpha was a pretty nice hall and Beta too.
Just more like home, like you lived at home, you know.
As a graduate student, did you have to wear a uniform?
No.
No, you wore civilian clothing.
Yeah, yeah.
But even at that point, did all the undergraduates have to wear uniforms?
In the cadet corps, yeah.
And that was, we thought that was the place to be then.
We really, I think we enjoyed it.
We know that from time to time a number of the students, in a sense, worked their way through school.
Did you ever have a job when you were in school?
I wish I had had.
My observation of the boys who worked the way through school made acquaintance with more professors and more administrators and I think they have an advantage.
Actually, the kid who worked his way through school.
Well, our President Ford worked his way through school.
But I did, my dad just
furnished me the money to come down here.
Now, for my master's though, after I was 21, I wouldn't take any more money from my dad.
And so I borrowed some money and then I got a scholarship down here.
And for my master's, we...

uh didn't have to wear a uniform but uh I didn't I didn't have to work away but they did borrow money to go to school and and they talk about our interest now well this is uh in the fall of 22 and I had to pay 10 interest on that money
That was from a bank?
Yeah.
But then, but the second semester of that graduate year, while you were doing some teaching, so you had an income.
Yes, yeah, I sure did.
Part-time.
And I'm presuming that helped out.
Yeah, it did.
It helped me pay that $300 off my bar.
Scholarship was just $200.
Of course, going to school then wasn't like it is now.
The scholarship was when you were working on your master's?
Yeah.
We know that at various times, on different occasions, there were girls who did attend classes.
Did you ever have any in your classes?
No.
About the only girls that went to A&M then were the daughters of the faculty.
I think Dr. Zell's daughter went to school here a little while, and maybe Dr. Fraps.
Dr. Fraps was state chemist over here.
He had a daughter I think went to school here.
and I don't know where Dr. Walden's, either went to school here or not, but there were a few girls like that, very few girls went to school here.
No thanks.
Okay.
I did a little checking in your 22,
Longhorn.
Did you?
You noted that you were on the international stock judging team.
Yes.
I presume that was on your senior year?
Yes.
How did you become a member of that?
By trying out for our, we had to, we'd take this livestock over here, and different barns, and they had hogs, beef cattle, horses, and sheep.
And you'd have classes to place and give reasons on.
Mr. Stangle, who was later dean out at Texas Tech, was our coach.
And he'd grade you on your placings and on your greasings.
And it was competitive.
You got on there by competition.
So how many of the students were on the team?
Five.
And each member, each one of each...
did you specialize in one type of lifestyle?
Everybody had to do all of them.
Now when I was a fish, we had a freshman lifestyle judging contest at the end of the freshman year.
And I looked out on that, I was high man of the freshman lifestyle judging contest and won a medal.
And in 1920 I lost that medal.
It was A.M. Walter medal.
It was a hexagon shaped thing and I lost it in 1920.
I did no work.
In 1940, 20 years later, we were going up to see our folks and we had a son at that time, nine years old.
We stopped at Leonard's other store in Fort Worth and bought an iron gun for him to shoot when he went up there.
So in Tuna, we lived on a city block and had a barn, an orchard and garden, chicken, all that kind of stuff.
So he was out there in the lot looking for something to put up on the fence to shoot at and kicked up that metal.
20 years after I lost it.
